  <span id="freeText4719233004673962548" style="display:none"><i>"You still love Terry Pratchett, after all these years?"<br>"Always."</i><br>- Gandalf, Return of the Jedi.<br><br>Jokes aside, <b>my teen years were marked by edginess, heavy metal, nihilism and Terry Pratchett.</b> I think the latter was never a phase; he is an author that will always be in my heart and in my head, <b>providing bellyache-inducing laughs whenever Death has an identity crisis</b> (which is always) or when <b>Nanny Ogg is trying to explain to her seemingly infinite children who their real fathers are</b>(and lying through her teeth).<br><br>Even though Rincewind and Twoflower aren't my favourites, <b>they still hold a special place in my heart because they were in the first Pratchett books I read.</b><br><br><i>courtesy of Jen's mini review</i><br><br><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1559063422i/27584707._SX540_.jpg" alt="Image result for rincewind and twoflower fanart" width="304" height="245" class="gr-hostedUserImg"></span>
